The paper discusses the distribution of attention on Twitter, which involves social interactions and information processing. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.SI (Social and Information Networks). The paper also analyzes the content of tweets, which suggests the sub-category cs.IR (Information Retrieval) as a likely second choice. The paper also discusses the relationship between interactional and informational attention processes, which could fall under the sub-category cs.CL (Computation and Language). Additionally, the paper discusses the hierarchical and heterogeneous nature of attention on Twitter, which could be related to the sub-categories cs.SOC (Social and Economic Networks) and cs.CYBER (Cybersecurity and Privacy).
